AGI - The Monaco Security Conference aroused a lot of fun the episode of the journalist who turned to Friedrich Merz > calling it "Chancellor", although in the elections there were still ten days and in office there was still Olaf Scholz>. The lapsus is however understandable: Unless the polls are clamorous, all the Germans take a big deal for granted that it will be the president of the Cdu to lead the government that will exit from the urns> of November 23. The question is, if anything, what will be the allies of the conservative leader, whose democratic-Christian Union, along with its Bavarian leg, the Csu, is given around 30%.
For one year Merz has claimed to want a coalition as low as possible, with one or more allies. And the alternatives are not many. After the unfortunate flirtation at the Bundestag last month, the EU leader excluded any collaboration with the Afd nationalists, now second party, given the 19.7% > by the last YouGov survey.
And it appears improposable any collaboration with the radical left parties, that is the Linke, in decisive increase over 7%>, and the philosopher Bundnis Sahra Wagenknecht (Bsw). This new party, born from a split of the same Linke, is likely not to exceed the threshold of 5% necessary to enter the Bundestag, as well as the liberals of the Fdp. And Merz wishes they both stay out.
The German electoral mechanism provides that the proportionate share conquered by the British who fail to exceed the landing is divided into the distribution of seats, by the parties represented at the Berlin Chamber. Merz hopes that Bsw and Fdp will not move so as to increase the representation of his Cdu and the two parties with which he has already declared to be willing to form a government: the Socialists of the SPD (15.6% according to YouGov) and the Greens (12.7%). If possible, only with one of the two and not both, he added. So let's see the possible scenarios.
<div </div
- GRANDE COALIZIONE (CDU/CSU + SPD)><br> That is the safe use. A formula already adopted four times in the history of post-war Germany, three of which under the gated Angela Merkel. The dialogue between Merz and Scholz > for a re-edition of the 'Grosse Koalition' has already started for weeks and has undergone further acceleration after the initial speech held last weekend in Munich by US Vice-President J.D. Vance, so much so that, according to the German media, there would already be a major understanding on the division of ministries. It must be said, however, that this time the co-existence between conservatives and socialists would be less simple than Merkel's times.
The former chancellor had not only moved the Union line to the left but had faced a Spd which, after Martin Schulz's exit, had entered a deep crisis that made it a very malleable interlocutor. There would be no too many problems for a relative tightening of migration policies: Scholz himself asked for easier expulsions for asylum seekers who have no title to remain in Germany after the last attacks committed by foreign citizens. It is predictable, on the other hand, a more heated comparison on the economic dossiers. Merz is for austerity; Scholz, during his government, significantly increased welfare costs and continues to demand more funds for social spending. If the increase in defence investment is all in agreement, somewhere we will have to cut. Nevertheless, a collaboration with the SPD would be the preferred option from Merz.<br> <br> - KIWI COALITION (CDU/CSU+VERDI)><br> The 'black' of the Union and the Green Party of the Vice Chancellor, Robert Habeck>, and the Foreign Minister, Annalena Baerbock. > This is a union never experienced at national level but at the government in more than one Land. The collapse of the 'Grunen' consensus makes this scenario unlikely, which would give Germany less stability than a fifth Great Coalition. If the line is similar on foreign policy, the Greens show a lot more resistance than the SPD to the immigration line promised by Merz.
<div </div
Not only that: the president of the Cdu would like a loosening of green policies to meet the demands of the industrialists, and an alliance with the ecologists would make a partial march back on this front very complicated. The leader of the Bavarian Csu, Markus Soeder, has in fact expressed a clear opposite to the hypothesis of a government with the Greens.&nbsp;
<div </div
- COALIZATION KENYA (CDU/CSU + SPD + VERDI)><br> The black, green and red of the Spd, like the colors of the flag of the African State. If at least one party between Bsw and Fdp exceeds the landing threshold, it would become difficult for the SPD and the Greens to have enough seats to be proposed as a solo partner for the Union. It is a coalition registered a few times locally and that Merz hopes not to have to consider, since it would force him to deal with two parties that, to the government from December 2021 with the Fdp (the so-called 'Jamaic Coalition'), have come into conflict several times in recent years. Depending on the verdict of the urns, the 'Kenya' option may, however, appear as an obligatory choice.<br> <br> - COALIZIONE GERMANIA (CDU/CSU + SPD + FDP)><br> The colors of the national flag. Instead of the green of the Kenya Coalition, there would be the liberal yellow, if they could enter the Bundestag. The Fdp is undoubtedly the closest party to the Union but, precisely because it draws on a similar basin, Merz invited voters not to waste their consent with the liberals in the name of the useful vote. However, it would be very difficult that Scholz would still want to cooperate with the President of the Fdp, Christian Lindner, his former Minister of Finance, who dropped his majority after a confrontation on public spending. It could be more functional a coalition between the Union, Greens and Fdp but the polls make it very unlikely to be realized.&nbsp;
